maize-94: estrtod() uses atof instead of strtod (printf %f/%e/%g).

Upstream file/function: libutil/estrtod.c, estrtod().
Why: Maize's freestanding libc (toolchain/rt/stdlib.c) provides atof but not yet
a real strtod (deferred to maize-244). printf.c calls estrtod for float-format
conversions; without this overlay the port cannot link (undefined strtod). The
endptr-driven "not a real number" diagnostic is dropped for wave 1: an honest,
recorded deviation, not a silent workaround. Revert this patch once maize-244
lands a real strtod.

diff --git a/libutil/estrtod.c b/libutil/estrtod.c
index 24e4fdc..41d97c3 100644
--- a/libutil/estrtod.c
+++ b/libutil/estrtod.c
@@ -8,11 +8,10 @@
 double
 estrtod(const char *s)
 {
-	char *end;
-	double d;
-
-	d = strtod(s, &end);
-	if (end == s || *end != '\0')
-		eprintf("%s: not a real number\n", s);
-	return d;
+	/* maize-94: Maize's freestanding libc (toolchain/rt) has no strtod yet
+	 * (deferred to maize-244); use atof, which stdlib.c provides. Best-effort
+	 * parse: strtod's endptr-driven "not a real number" diagnostic on trailing
+	 * garbage / empty input is dropped for wave 1, when printf %f/%e/%g accept
+	 * an atof-grade conversion. printf's caller already guards strlen(arg) > 0. */
+	return atof(s);
 }
